<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-02-28c.49.5" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100164" speakername="Lord Davies of Oldham" colon=":" colnum="49"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds06/text/60228w04.htm#60228w04_spnew3">
	<p pid="c.49.5/1">Total public expenditure on transport services, across the UK, rose in real terms by 67 per cent. between 1997&ndash;98 and 2004&ndash;05.</p>
	<p pid="c.49.5/2">Local authorities fund the majority of their support for bus services, including those in rural areas, from their revenue support grant allocations from government. Decisions on which services to support&mdash;and by how much&mdash;are a matter for individual local authorities and no statistics are kept centrally on total support for services that are specifically rural. Over &pound;300 million was spent on bus support by local authorities in England outside London in 2004&ndash;05, an increase of 43 per cent. in real terms since 1997.</p>
	<p pid="c.49.5/3">Local authority bus expenditure includes that met from rural bus subsidy grant (RBSG) provided to authorities by the department to help maintain and improve rural bus services. RBSG has totalled &pound;340 million since its introduction in 1998. The total allocation for 2005&ndash;06 is &pound;53 million, a 41 per cent. increase in real terms compared with 1998&ndash;99. In addition, we have since 1998&ndash;99 allocated a total of &pound;114 million in Rural Bus Challenge and Kickstart funding for rural areas.</p>
</reply>
